Accordingly, the text of the edition of this speech published by Classen at Bonn in 1831, and accompanied by elaborate critical notes, is founded upon these two MSS„ and assumes a shape differing materially from the vulgate.

Again‚ in 1854, appeared what is termed in the title page the ‘second edition improved,’ ‘editio altera emendatior,’ of Orelli’s Cicero, published under the superintendence of Baiter and Halm. But, as far as regards this speech, it ought rather to be designated as a second edition of Classen’s text. For although Baiter has not servilely followed Classen, he has, on almost all the most important points, adopted his views, and very rarely adheres to those of Orelli.

Lastly, in 1856 was published that volume of Mr. Long’s edition of the speeches of Cicero—a work of which Ι would speak with great respect—which contains the oration for Cluentius. Mr. Long professes to have modelled his text upon the labours of Classen and Baiter3 and therefore, where 1 have been unable to adopt their views, I have been com- pelled to differ from him also.
